726977f-a.title: Queens: Jamaica Avenue - 153rd Street
726977f-a.text:
Jamaica Ave., north side, between 153rd Street (left, not seen) and Parsons Boulevard (right), showing across the Grace Cemetery, homes on the west side of 155th Street. This view shows the Grace Protestant
Episcopal Church which was opened to worship in 1862.
About 1910.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

727043f-a.title: Queens: Jamaica Avenue - 153rd Street
727043f-a.text:
Jamaica Ave., south side, east of 153rd Street, showing in a set of three views the First Dutch ReformoKChurch of Jamaica. The present edifice is one of the three structures erected on this site. The first was erected in 1716 and was an octagon in shape; the second was built in 1832 and was destroyed by fire in 1857; the Dresent one, on which construction was started in 1858, had its cornerstone laid on September 14, 1858 by Richard Brush. Dr. Thomas E. Vermilge dedicated it on October 6, 1859. This structure was erected
at a cost of 20,000.
October 1923.
Views 2 & 3: April 1925.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
